<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM23460 - Shares that may be awarded: No restrictions on eligible shares</h1>
<p>The restrictions that infringe paragraph 30(1) are restrictions to which the eligible shares are subject (see below), which </p>
<ul>
<li>do not affect all ordinary shares in the same company (see below), or</li>
<li>which are not  “permitted restrictions” (see <a href="ESSUM23420.htm">ESSUM23420</a>).</li>
</ul>
<p>A restriction only attaches to a share if the share was subject to the restriction on issue by virtue of the company's Articles of Association or by authority of a special resolution of the company (or a later amendment to the company's Articles).</p>
<p>Paragraph 30 is concerned with restrictions to which the eligible shares (the shares which will be acquired by the participants in the plan) are subject. Restrictions that apply only to shares of other classes, or to shares of the same class which are not to be eligible shares, are not covered by paragraph 30.</p>
<p>Restrictions on eligible shares can take the form of: </p>
<ul>
<li>direct restrictions on the eligible shares, or </li>
<li>additional rights given to other shares.</li>
</ul>
<p>Restrictions attaching to shares are most commonly, but not exclusively, to be found in the section of the Articles governing share transfers.  In examining the Articles of Association in relation to a particular class of shares the scheme advisor should look for:</p>
<ul>
<li>direct restrictions on shares which will only apply to shares held by employees,  and/or</li>
<li>rights given to other shareholders which employee shareholders do not have.</li>
</ul>
<p>Scheme advisors should also check whether new shares to be issued to the trustees of a SIP will rank equally in all respects ("pari-passu") with the ordinary shares already in issue.  If newly-issued shares will be subject to restrictions, those restrictions must satisfy the requirements of paragraph 30(1).</p>
